Since you need **three** themes (not just light/dark), use the **ResourceDictionary swap** approach. `AppThemeBinding` only supports two themes.

## Setup

### 1. Create three ResourceDictionary files with matching keys

**Themes/LightTheme.xaml**
```xml
<ResourceDictionary xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
                    xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
                    x:Class="MyApp.Themes.LightTheme">
    <Color x:Key="PageBackgroundColor">White</Color>
    <Color x:Key="PrimaryTextColor">#333333</Color>
    <Color x:Key="AccentColor">#2196F3</Color>
</ResourceDictionary>
```

**Themes/DarkTheme.xaml** — same keys, dark values:
```xml
    <Color x:Key="PageBackgroundColor">#1E1E1E</Color>
    <Color x:Key="PrimaryTextColor">#F0F0F0</Color>
    <Color x:Key="AccentColor">#BB86FC</Color>
```

**Themes/HighContrastTheme.xaml** — same keys, high-contrast values:
```xml
    <Color x:Key="PageBackgroundColor">Black</Color>
    <Color x:Key="PrimaryTextColor">White</Color>
    <Color x:Key="AccentColor">Yellow</Color>
```

Each needs a code-behind calling `InitializeComponent()`:
```csharp
public partial class LightTheme : ResourceDictionary
{
    public LightTheme() => InitializeComponent();
}
```

### 2. Use `DynamicResource` everywhere (not `StaticResource`)

```xml
<ContentPage BackgroundColor="{DynamicResource PageBackgroundColor}">
    <Label Text="Hello" TextColor="{DynamicResource PrimaryTextColor}" />
    <Button Text="Action" BackgroundColor="{DynamicResource AccentColor}" />
</ContentPage>
```

### 3. Create a theme service to swap dictionaries

```csharp
public static class ThemeService
{
    public static void ApplyTheme(string themeName)
    {
        var mergedDicts = Application.Current!.Resources.MergedDictionaries;
        mergedDicts.Clear();
        mergedDicts.Add(themeName switch
        {
            "Dark"         => new DarkTheme(),
            "HighContrast"  => new HighContrastTheme(),
            _              => new LightTheme()
        });

        Preferences.Set("AppTheme", themeName);
    }

    public static void RestoreSavedTheme()
    {
        var saved = Preferences.Get("AppTheme", "Light");
        ApplyTheme(saved);
    }
}
```

### 4. Call `RestoreSavedTheme()` on startup (in `App` constructor)

```csharp
public App()
{
    InitializeComponent();
    ThemeService.RestoreSavedTheme();
}
```

### 5. Wire up your settings page

```csharp
// In your settings page or ViewModel:
void OnThemeSelected(string theme) => ThemeService.ApplyTheme(theme);
```

## Key pitfalls to avoid

- **Every `x:Key` must exist in all three dictionaries** — missing keys silently fall back to defaults.
- **Android**: ensure `MainActivity` includes `ConfigChanges.UiMode` or theme changes cause a full activity restart.
- **Never use `StaticResource`** for themed values — they freeze at first load and won't update on swap.
